solution:
Since $\nabla^{2} \varphi=\frac{\rho}{\varepsilon_{0}}$, in spherical coordinates when $r \neq 0$,

$$
\nabla^{2} \varphi=\frac{1}{r^{2}} \cdot \frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2} \frac{\partial \varphi}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2} \sin \theta} \cdot \frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\left(\sin \theta \frac{\partial \varphi}{\partial \theta}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2} \sin^{2} \theta} \cdot \frac{\partial^{2} \varphi}{\partial \varphi^{2}}
$$

Given $\varphi=\frac{A}{r} \mathrm{e}^{-\mu r}$, substitute it into the equation above:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\nabla^{2} \varphi & =\frac{1}{r^{2}} \cdot \frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left[r^{2} \frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(\frac{A}{r} \mathrm{e}^{-\mu r}\right)\right]+0 \\
& =\frac{1}{r^{2}} \cdot \frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left[r^{2}\left(-\frac{A}{r^{2}} \mathrm{e}^{-\mu r}-\frac{A \mu}{r} \mathrm{e}^{-\mu r}\right)\right] \\
& =\frac{\mu^{2} A}{r} \mathrm{e}^{-\mu r}
\end{aligned}
$$

From the Poisson's equation for electrostatic fields:

$$
\nabla^{2} \varphi=-\frac{\rho}{\varepsilon_{0}}
$$

we obtain

$$
\rho=-\frac{\mu^{2} A \varepsilon_{0}}{r} \mathrm{e}^{-\mu r}
$$

Suppose an electric dipole $\boldsymbol{P} = P \boldsymbol{e}_{r}$ is placed at the origin of the coordinate system. The potential it generates at position $\boldsymbol{r}$ is given by

\begin{equation*}
\varphi = -\frac{1}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}} \boldsymbol{P} \cdot \nabla \frac{1}{r} = \frac{P \cos \theta}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r^{2}} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

Comparing equation (3) with the second term of equation (2), the second term of equation (2) corresponds to the contribution from a dipole

$$
\boldsymbol{P} = 4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} a^{3} \boldsymbol{E}_{0}
$$

which represents the induced electric dipole moment of the sphere.

Since the charge \(Q\) remains constant, the final voltage is determined by:

\[
\begin{aligned}
& C U = C^{\prime} U^{\prime} \\
& U^{\prime} = 2 U = 2000 \, \mathrm{V}
\end{aligned}
\]

The interaction energy is given by

\[
\begin{align*}
W & = \int \varphi(r) \, \mathrm{d} q = \int \varphi(\boldsymbol{r}) \rho(r) \, \mathrm{d} v \\
& = -\frac{q_{0}^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} a^{3}} \int \frac{1}{r} e^{-\frac{2}{a} r} r^{2} \sin \theta \, \mathrm{d} r \, \mathrm{d} \theta \, \mathrm{d} \phi \tag{2} \\
& = -\frac{q_{0}^{2}}{\varepsilon_{0} a^{3}} \int_{0}^{\infty} r e^{-\frac{2}{a} r} \, \mathrm{d} r = -\frac{q_{0}^{2}}{\varepsilon_{0} a}
\end{align*}
\]

When the radius changes from \( r_{1} \) to \( r_{2} = 1 \mathrm{~mm} \), the change in electric energy is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta w & = \frac{Q^{2}}{8 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r_{2}} - \frac{Q^{2}}{8 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r_{1}} = 2 \pi \varepsilon_{0}\left(r_{1} V_{1}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{1}{r_{2}} - \frac{1}{r_{1}}\right) \\
& = 2 \pi \times 8.85 \times 10^{-12} \,\text{(F/m)} \times \left(10^{-2} \,\text{(m)} \times 100 \,\text{(V)}\right)^{2} \times \left(\frac{1}{10^{-3} \,\text{(m)}} - \frac{1}{10^{-2} \,\text{(m)}}\right) \\
& = 5 \times 10^{-8} \,\text{(J)}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
V(r) = V_{0} - \int_{r_{1}}^{r} \boldsymbol{E} \cdot \mathrm{d}r = \frac{V_{0} \ln \left(r_{2} / r\right)}{\ln \left(r_{2} / r_{1}\right)}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
B & = \frac{\mu_{0} N I}{l} = \frac{4 \pi \times 10^{-7} \times 1000 \times 2000}{2} \\
& = 1.26 \, (\mathrm{Wb} / \mathrm{m}^{2})
\end{aligned}
$$

(b) The magnetic energy density is given by $w_{m} = \frac{B^{2}}{2 \mu_{0}} = \frac{\mu_{0}}{2}\left(\frac{i}{2 \pi r}\right)^{2}$. Hence, the magnetic energy per unit length is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\mathrm{d} w_{m}}{\mathrm{~d} z} &= \int w_{m} \mathrm{~d} s = \int_{R_{1}}^{R_{2}} \frac{\mu_{0}}{2} \left(\frac{i}{2 \pi r}\right)^{2} \cdot 2 \pi r \mathrm{~d} r \\
&= \frac{\mu_{0} i^{2}}{4 \pi} \ln \frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}}
\end{aligned}
$$

The electric energy density is given by $w_{e} = \frac{\varepsilon_{0} E^{2}}{2} = \frac{\varepsilon_{0}}{2}\left(\frac{V}{r \ln \frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}}}\right)^{2}$. Hence, the electric energy per unit length is

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d} w_{e}}{\mathrm{~d} z} = \int w_{e} \mathrm{~d} s = \frac{\pi \varepsilon_{0} V^{2}}{\ln \frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}}}
$$

When the distance between the plates of the capacitor is doubled, the capacitor's capacitance becomes $C^{\prime}=\frac{C}{2}$, where $C=\frac{\varepsilon_{0} A}{d}$ is the original capacitance before the gap is increased. When the capacitor is charged to $U=1000 \, \mathrm{V}$, the charge on the capacitor is $Q=C U$. As the gap is widened, the charge $Q$ remains unchanged. The change in stored energy of the capacitor during the process of widening the gap is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta W & =\frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{Q^{2}}{C^{\prime}}-\frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{Q^{2}}{C}=\frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{Q^{2}}{C}=\frac{1}{2} C U^{2} \\
& =\frac{\varepsilon_{0} A U^{2}}{2 d}=\frac{8.9 \times 10^{-12} \times 0.2 \times\left(10^{3}\right)^{2}}{2 \times 0.01} \\
& =8.9 \times 10^{-5} \, \mathrm{J}
\end{aligned}
$$

$\Delta W$ is the work required to double the gap between the plates.

Neglecting gravity, the equations of motion for the electrons are

\[
\begin{align*}
& m \frac{\mathrm{d} v_{x}}{\mathrm{d} t}=-e\left(-\frac{\partial \phi}{\partial x}+v_{y} B_{0}\right) \tag{1}\\
& m \frac{\mathrm{d} v_{y}}{\mathrm{d} t}=e v_{x} B_{0} \tag{2}\\
& m \frac{\mathrm{d} v_{z}}{\mathrm{d} t}=0 \tag{3}
\end{align*}
\]

From equation (3), we obtain

\[
\begin{gathered}
v_{z}(t)=v_{z}(t=0)=0 \\
z(t)=z(t=0)=\text{constant}
\end{gathered}
\]

Thus, the coordinate and velocity of the electrons in the \(z\) direction are constants of motion.

For the electron to maintain constant velocity, the net force acting on the electron must be zero, i.e.,

$$
\boldsymbol{F}_{\mathrm{B}}=-\boldsymbol{F}_{\mathrm{E}}=-e E \mathbf{e}_{x}
$$

However, $\boldsymbol{F}_{\mathrm{B}}=-e \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{B}=-e B v \times \mathbf{e}_{z}$, thus it is immediately known that

\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{v}=-\left(\frac{E}{B}\right) \mathbf{e}_{y} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The energy carried by the pulse is distributed as electric field energy and magnetic field energy along the transmission line. The length of the distribution is

\[
l = v t = 2.5 \times 10^{8} \times 10^{-8} = 2.5 \, \text{m}
\]

Therefore,

\[
\begin{aligned}
W_{\mathrm{c}} &= \frac{1}{2}(C l) \cdot V^{2} = \frac{1}{2}\left(4 \times 10^{-11} \times 2.5\right) \times 15^{2} = 1.125 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{J} \\
W_{\mathrm{m}} &= \frac{1}{2}(L l) I^{2} = \frac{1}{2} \times 4 \times 10^{-7} \times 2.5 \times 0.15^{2} = 1.125 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{J}
\end{aligned}
\]

From $\nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{B}=\mu_{0} \rho_{\mathrm{m}}$, by choosing a spherical surface $S$ with radius $r$, the following integral gives

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \int_{V} \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{B} \, \mathrm{d} V=\oint_{S} \boldsymbol{B} \cdot \mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{S}=4 \pi r^{2} B(r)=\mu_{0} q_{\mathrm{m}} \\
& \boldsymbol{B}(r)=\frac{\mu_{0} q_{\mathrm{m}}}{4 \pi r^{2}} \boldsymbol{e}_{\mathrm{r}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Referring to the illustration in Figure 1.111, the vector \(\boldsymbol{r}\) points from \(\boldsymbol{P}_{1}\) to \(\boldsymbol{P}_{2}\). Treat the electric field produced by \(\boldsymbol{P}_{1}\) as an external field, with the electric field intensity at \(P_{2}\) given by

\[
\boldsymbol{E}_{e} = \frac{3\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{r} - r^{2} \boldsymbol{P}_{1}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r^{5}}
\]

Therefore, the interaction force between \(\boldsymbol{P}_{1}\) and \(\boldsymbol{P}_{2}\) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{F} & = \boldsymbol{P}_{2} \cdot \nabla \boldsymbol{E}_{e} \\
& = \frac{3}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r^{7}}\left\{r^{2}\left[\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{P}_{2}\right) \boldsymbol{r} + \left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{P}_{2} + \left(\boldsymbol{P}_{2} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{P}_{1}\right] - 5\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{1} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right)\left(\boldsymbol{P}_{2} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}\right) \boldsymbol{r}\right\}
\end{aligned}
\]

According to the problem, everywhere:

$$
\begin{aligned}
B_{r}(r, z) &= -v B_{0} r z \\
B_{z}(r, z) &= B_{0} \left(1 + v z^{2}\right) \boldsymbol{e}_{z}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using $\boldsymbol{j} = \frac{1}{\mu_{0}} \nabla \times \boldsymbol{B}$, noting $B_{\theta} = 0, \frac{\partial B_{r}}{\partial \theta} = \frac{\partial B_{z}}{\partial \theta} = 0$, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{j}(r, z) &= \frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\left[\frac{\partial B_{r}}{\partial z} - \frac{\partial B_{z}}{\partial r}\right] \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta} = \frac{1}{\mu_{0}} \cdot \frac{\partial B_{r}}{\partial z} \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta} \\
&= -\frac{1}{\mu_{0}} v B_{0} r \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta}
\end{aligned}
$$

The surface charge on the surfaces at \( r=r_{0} \) and \( r=r_{0}+\Delta r \) is as follows:

\[
\begin{gathered}
\sigma\left(r_{0}\right)=\varepsilon_{0}\left[E_{2}\left(r_{0}\right)-E_{1}\left(r_{0}\right)\right] \\
\quad=\varepsilon_{0}\left[0-\frac{\rho_{0} r_{0}}{2 \varepsilon_{0}}\right]=-\frac{\rho_{0} r_{0}}{2}
\end{gathered}
\]

\[
\begin{gathered}
\sigma\left(r_{0}+\Delta r\right)=\varepsilon_{0} E_{2}\left(r_{0}+\Delta r\right) \\
=\frac{\rho_{0} r_{0}^{2}}{2\left(r_{0}+\Delta r\right)}
\end{gathered}
\]

Referring to Problem 2.39, the magnetic fields inside and outside the sphere are given by

\[
\begin{array}{lr}
\boldsymbol{B}_{1}=\frac{2}{3} \mu_{0} \sigma \omega R \boldsymbol{e}_{z}, & r \leqslant R \\
\boldsymbol{B}_{2}=\frac{\mu_{0}}{3} \sigma R^{3}\left(\frac{3(\boldsymbol{\omega} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}) \boldsymbol{r}}{r^{5}}-\frac{\boldsymbol{\omega}}{r^{3}}\right), & r>R  \tag{5}
\end{array}
\]

From equation (5), it is apparent that the magnitude of the magnetic field inside the sphere is

\begin{equation*}
B_{1}=\frac{2}{3} \mu_{0} \sigma \omega R \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

which is a constant, hence it represents a uniform field. Additionally, as the magnetic field formula for a dipole with magnetic moment \(\boldsymbol{m}\) is \(\frac{\mu_{0}}{4 \pi}\left[\frac{3(\boldsymbol{m} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}) \boldsymbol{r}}{r^{5}}-\frac{\boldsymbol{m}}{r^{3}}\right]\), it follows from equation (5) that the magnetic field outside the sphere corresponds to that of a magnetic dipole with

\begin{equation*}
m=\frac{4 \pi}{3} \sigma R^{4} \omega e_{z} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

Using \( e_{z}=\cos \theta e_{r}-\sin \theta e_{\theta} \), rewrite equation (5) as

\begin{align*}
& \boldsymbol{B}_{1}=\frac{2}{3} \mu_{0} \sigma \omega R\left(\cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{r}-\sin \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta}\right)  \tag{8}\\
& \boldsymbol{B}_{2}=\frac{\mu_{0} \sigma \omega R^{4}}{3 r^{3}}\left(2 \cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{r}+\sin \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta}\right) \tag{9}
\end{align*}

It is evident that equations (8) and (9) satisfy the boundary conditions given by equations (1) and (3).

The boundary conditions at the surface of the conductor are:

\begin{align*}
& \varphi=\text{constant} \\
& \varepsilon_{0} \frac{\partial \varphi}{\partial r}=-\sigma \tag{1}
\end{align*}

where $\varphi$ is the electric potential outside the sphere, and $\sigma$ is the surface charge density on the sphere. Referencing question 1.74, using the method of separation of variables, we can solve to find:

\begin{equation*}
\varphi=-E_{0} r \cos \theta+\frac{E_{0} a^{3}}{r^{2}} \cos \theta \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

where $a$ is the radius of the conducting sphere. Thus, from equation (1), we obtain:

$$
\sigma=3 \varepsilon_{0} E_{0} \cos \theta
$$

From the previously determined magnetic field distribution, we can obtain the current density distribution within the cylinder using the differential form of Ampère's circuital law as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{j} &= \frac{1}{\mu_{0}} \nabla \times \boldsymbol{B} = \frac{1}{\mu_{0}} \left[\frac{\partial B_{r}}{\partial z} - \frac{\partial B_{z}}{\partial r}\right] \boldsymbol{e}_{\phi} \\
&= -\frac{1}{\mu_{0}} B_{0}(\beta + 2 \alpha) \boldsymbol{e}_{\phi}
\end{aligned}
$$

Here, $\boldsymbol{e}_{\phi}$ is the angular unit vector in cylindrical coordinates. From the above result, we know that the current density vector $\boldsymbol{j}$ is directed azimuthally.

The work required to move \( q \) to infinity is given by

\[
\begin{aligned}
W & = \int_{a}^{\infty} F \, \mathrm{d} r = \int_{a}^{\infty} \frac{1}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}} \frac{q^{2}}{(2r)^{2}} \, \mathrm{d} r = \frac{q^{2}}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{0} a} \\
& = 0.09 \, \mathrm{J}
\end{aligned}
\]

answers:
\[
\boxed{\frac{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} K_{1} K_{2} a b c d}{K_{1} a b(d-c)+K_{1} K_{2} a d(c-b)+K_{2} c d(b-a)}}
\]

solution:
At the point \((0,0,-a^{-})\), the electric field strength is

\[
\boldsymbol{E} = -\frac{q}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}}\left[\frac{1}{r a}+\frac{1}{(r+a)^{2}}-\frac{r / a}{(r+a)^{2}}\right] \boldsymbol{e}_{z}
\]

If \(q \rightarrow -q\), then at \((0,0,-a)\) there is the largest negative induced surface charge density. From above, the required \(Q\) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
Q & > -\sigma \cdot 4 \pi a^{2} = -\varepsilon_{0} \cdot 4 \pi a^{2}\left(\frac{-q}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}}\right) \cdot\left[\frac{1}{r a}+\frac{1}{(r+a)^{2}}-\frac{r / a}{(r+a)^{2}}\right] \\
& = q\left[\frac{a}{r}+\frac{a^{2}}{(r+a)^{2}}-\frac{a r}{(r+a)^{2}}\right] = \frac{q a^{2}(3 r+a)}{r(r+a)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

The magnetic torque experienced by the rotating small loop is given by

\[
\begin{aligned}
\tau & = |\boldsymbol{m} \times \boldsymbol{B}| = \pi r_{1}^{2} i B \sin \omega t = \pi r_{1}^{2} i \cdot \frac{\mu_{0} I}{2 r_{2}} \sin \omega t \\
& = \frac{\mu_{0}^{2} \pi^{2} I^{2} \omega r_{1}^{4} \sin^{2} \omega t}{4 R r_{2}^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(\boldsymbol{m}\) is the magnetic moment of the small loop. For the small loop to rotate uniformly, the external torque \(\boldsymbol{\tau}_{\text{ext}}\) must balance the magnetic torque \(\boldsymbol{\tau}\), i.e., \(\boldsymbol{\tau}_{\text{ext}} = \boldsymbol{\tau}\).

Let the capacitances of the metal plate and the conductor be $C_{1}$ and $C_{2}$, respectively. When the metal plate is charged with $Q$, its potential is $U^{*}$. Thus, we have $Q = C_{1} U^{*}$. After the metal plate is in contact with the conductor, the charge moves to the conductor of lower potential, and upon reaching equilibrium, the charge on the conductor is $q$. By the conservation of charge, the remaining charge on the metal plate is $Q-q$. The potentials of the metal plate and the conductor are given by

$$
U_{1} = \frac{Q-q}{C_{1}}, \quad U_{2} = \frac{q}{C_{2}}
$$

With the condition $U_{1} = U_{2} < U^{*}$.

After removing the conductor, the metal plate is recharged to $Q$, with a potential of $U^{*}$, where $U^{*} > U_{2}$. Thus, when the conductor contacts the metal plate again, the charge on the plate continues to move to the conductor. Once the conductor is removed, the metal plate is recharged to $Q$, and the process repeats. The charge on the conductor continues to increase until it reaches a value $q^{*}$, such that its potential equals the potential of the metal plate charged to $Q$, $U^{*}$. Therefore, the final charge on the conductor is

$$
\begin{aligned}
q^{*} &= C_{2} U^{*} = C_{2} \frac{Q}{C_{1}} \\
&= Q \frac{\frac{q}{U_{2}}}{\frac{Q-q}{U_{1}}} = \frac{Q q}{Q-q}
\end{aligned}
$$

Let the charge, mass, and angular momentum of the particle be $q, m, L$ respectively. Since the problem asks for the steady component of the field, the excitation source can be treated as a steady current loop. The vector potential is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{A}(\boldsymbol{R}) & =\frac{\mu_{0}}{4 \pi} \int \frac{J\left(r^{\prime}\right)}{r} \mathrm{~d} V^{\prime} \\
& =\frac{\mu_{0}}{4 \pi} \int J\left(r^{\prime}\right)\left(\frac{1}{R}-\boldsymbol{r}^{\prime} \cdot \nabla \frac{1}{R}\right) \mathrm{d} V^{\prime}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& = \frac{\mu_{0}}{4 \pi} \left(\frac{I}{2} \oint \boldsymbol{r}^{\prime} \cdot \mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{r}^{\prime}\right) \times \frac{\boldsymbol{R}}{R^{3}} \\
& = \frac{\mu_{0}}{4 \pi} I \cdot \pi r^{2} \boldsymbol{e}_{z} \times \frac{\boldsymbol{R}}{R^{3}} = \frac{\mu_{0} q}{8 \pi m} \boldsymbol{L} \times \frac{\boldsymbol{R}}{R^{3}}
\end{aligned}
$$

$R$ is the position vector of the observation point from the origin. From $B=\nabla \times \boldsymbol{A}$, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{B} & = \frac{\mu_{0} q}{8 \pi m} \nabla \times \left(\boldsymbol{L} \times \frac{\boldsymbol{R}}{R^{3}}\right) = -\frac{\mu_{0} q}{8 \pi m}(\boldsymbol{L} \cdot \nabla) \frac{\boldsymbol{R}}{R^{3}} \\
& = \frac{\mu_{0} q L}{8 \pi m}\left(\frac{3 \cos \theta}{R^{3}} \boldsymbol{e}_{R} - \frac{\boldsymbol{e}_{z}}{R^{3}}\right) = \frac{\mu_{0} q L}{8 \pi m R^{3}}\left(3 \cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{R} - \boldsymbol{e}_{z}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The potential at a distant point is

\[
\begin{align*}
\varphi & \approx \varphi^{(0)}+\varphi^{(2)}=\frac{1}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}} \cdot \frac{Q}{R}+\frac{1}{24 \pi \varepsilon_{0}} \sum D_{ij} \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x_{i} \partial x_{j}} \cdot \frac{1}{R} \\
& =\frac{k a^{3}}{6 \varepsilon_{0} R}+\frac{k a^{5}}{40 \varepsilon_{0} R^{3}}\left(1-3 \cos^{2} \theta\right) \tag{3}
\end{align*}
\]

Using the method of image charges. Let the distance from the charge \( q \) to the center of the sphere be \( a \). The image charge is \( q' = -\frac{r_{1}}{a} q \), and \( q' \) is located at \( b = \frac{r_{1}^{2}}{a} \) (as shown in figure 1.102). Since the conducting spherical shell is isolated and uncharged, it forms an equipotential body with potential \( \varphi = \varphi_{0} \). Therefore, the electric field inside the cavity \(\left(r<r_{1}\right)\) should be equal to the electric field produced by \( q \) and \( q' \).

The force on charge \( q \) can equivalently be determined by the force due to \( q' \), which is

$$
\begin{aligned}
F & = \frac{q q'}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} (b-a)^{2}} = -\frac{\frac{r_{1}}{a} q^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} \left(\frac{r_{1}^{2}}{a} - a\right)^{2}} \\
& = -\frac{a r_{1} q^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} \left(r_{1}^{2} - a^{2}\right)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

According to Maxwell's equation $\nabla \times \boldsymbol{E} = -\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{B}}{\partial t}$, similar to the solution in part (b), the electric field direction is along the $z$ direction, i.e., $E_{\phi} = 0, E_{\rho} = 0$. For the region $r_1 < r < r_2$, we have

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
E_{z}(r) = E_{0} - \frac{\mu_{0} r^{2}}{4 \pi r_{1}^{2}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d} I}{\mathrm{d} t}, & 0 < r < r_{1} \\
E_{z}(r) = E_{0} - \frac{\mu_{0}}{2 \pi}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\ln \frac{r}{r_{1}}\right) \frac{\mathrm{d} I}{\mathrm{d} t}, & r_{1} < r < r_{2} \\
E_{z}(r) = E_{0} - \frac{\mu_{0}}{2 \pi}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\ln \frac{r_{2}}{r_{1}}\right) \frac{\mathrm{d} I}{\mathrm{d} t}, & r > r_{2}
\end{array}
$$

where $E_{0}$ is the electric field strength in the $z$ direction at $r = 0$.

Finally, the electric potentials inside and outside the cylinder are obtained as:
\begin{align*}
& \varphi_{1} = \frac{\sigma_{2}}{2 \varepsilon_{0}} r \cos \theta + \frac{\sigma_{1}}{4 \varepsilon_{0} R} r^{2} \sin 2 \theta \\
& \varphi_{2} = \frac{\sigma_{2} R^{2}}{2 \varepsilon_{0} r} \cos \theta + \frac{\sigma_{1} R^{3}}{4 \varepsilon_{0} r^{2}} \sin 2 \theta
\end{align*}

The external force acting on the cloud is the electrostatic force between the image charges and the charges in the cloud

$$
\begin{aligned}
F & = \frac{q^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0}} \left[-\frac{1}{(2d)^{2}} + \frac{1}{(3d)^{2}} + \frac{1}{(3d)^{2}} - \frac{1}{(4d)^{2}}\right] \\
& = \frac{q^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} d^{2}} \left[\frac{2}{9} - \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{16}\right] = -4.05 \times 10^{-3} \, \mathrm{N}
\end{aligned}
$$

This force is an attractive force, as shown in Figure 1.93 in the original problem.

In the particle's coordinate system \( xyz \), the magnetic field \( \boldsymbol{B} \) is given as

$$
\boldsymbol{B} = B \sin \theta \cos \varphi \, \boldsymbol{e}_{x} + B \sin \theta \sin \varphi \, \boldsymbol{e}_{y} + B \cos \theta \, \boldsymbol{e}_{z}
$$

When \( \left|\chi_{x}\right|, \left|\chi_{y}\right|, \left|\chi_{z}\right| \) are much less than 1 (which is generally the case), the magnetic field inside the particle (i.e., the small cylinder) can also be considered as \( \boldsymbol{B} \). The magnetization intensity is given by

$$
\boldsymbol{M} = \boldsymbol{\chi} \cdot \boldsymbol{H} = \boldsymbol{\chi} \cdot \frac{\boldsymbol{B}}{\mu_{0}}
$$

Assuming the volume of the small cylinder is \( V \), the aligning energy is calculated as

$$
\begin{aligned}
E &= \boldsymbol{M} \cdot \boldsymbol{B} = \boldsymbol{B} \cdot \left(\boldsymbol{\chi} \cdot \frac{\boldsymbol{B}}{\mu_{0}} V\right) \\
&= \frac{V}{\mu_{0}}\left(B_{x}, \quad B_{y}, \quad B_{z}\right)\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\chi_{x} & & \\
& \chi_{y} & \\
& & \chi_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
B_{x} \\
B_{y} \\
B_{z}
\end{array}\right) \\
&= \frac{V}{\mu_{0}}\left(\chi_{x} B_{x}^{2} + \chi_{y} B_{y}^{2} + \chi_{z} B_{z}^{2}\right) \\
&= \frac{V}{\mu_{0}}\left[\chi_{x}\left(B_{x}^{2} + B_{y}^{2}\right) + \chi_{z} B_{z}^{2}\right] \\
&= \frac{V}{\mu_{0}}\left(\chi_{x} B^{2} \sin^{2} \theta + \chi_{z} B^{2} \cos^{2} \theta\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, at

\[
\left.\phi\right|_{r=R} \approx \sum_{l=0}^{3} \frac{A_{l}}{R^{l+1}} P_{l} = \sum_{l=0}^{3} B_{l} P_{l}
\]

Therefore,

\[
A_{l}=R^{l+1} B_{l}
\]

The final result is:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\phi & \approx \sum_{l=0}^{3} B_{l}\left(\frac{R}{r}\right)^{l+1} P_{l}(\cos \theta) \\
