\end{equation*}

In this problem, since $\phi(r, \theta) = \phi(r, -\theta)$, the sine terms are not included in equation (2). Divide the space inside and outside the cylinder into three parts as shown in the diagram. The general solution $\phi$ for each part is of the form

\begin{equation*}
\phi_{i} = \sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(c_{i m} r^{m} + d_{i m}\right) \cos m \theta, \quad i=1, 2, 3 \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

For the external region of the cylinder, as $r \rightarrow \infty$, $\phi_{3} = -H_{0} r \cos \theta$, $\mu_{0} H = B_{0}$. From equation (3) we have

$$
c_{31} = -\frac{B_{0}}{\mu_{0}}, \quad c_{3 m} = d_{3 m} = 0, \quad m \neq 1
$$

Hence

\begin{equation*}
\phi_{3} = -\left(\frac{B_{0}}{\mu_{0}} r - \frac{d_{31}}{r}\right) \cos \theta \tag{4}
\end{equation*}

From the boundary conditions at $r = a, b$, we have

\begin{gather*}
\mu_{0} \frac{\partial \phi_{3}}{\partial r} = \left.\mu \frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial r}\right|_{r=a}  \tag{5}\\
\mu_{0} \frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial r} = \left.\mu \frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial r}\right|_{r=b} \\
\frac{\partial \phi_{3}}{\partial \theta} = \left.\frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial \theta}\right|_{r=a}, \quad \frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial \theta} = \left.\frac{\partial \phi_{2}}{\partial \theta}\right|_{r=b} \tag{6}
\end{gather*}

Combining equations (3) and (6), we obtain a system of equations

\[
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
B_{0} + \frac{\mu_{0} d_{31}}{a^{2}} = \mu\left(-c_{21} + \frac{d_{21}}{a^{2}}\right)  \tag{7}\\
-B_{0} + \frac{d_{31}}{a^{2}} = \mu_{0}\left(c_{21} + \frac{d_{21}}{a^{2}}\right) \\
\mu\left(c_{21} - \frac{d_{21}}{b^{2}}\right) = \mu_{0} c_{11} \\
c_{21} + \frac{d_{21}}{b^{2}} = c_{11}
\end{array}\right.
\]

Additionally, since $\phi_{1}$ must be finite at $r = 0$, we have

\begin{equation*}
d_{11} = 0 \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

The magnetic scalar potential inside the cylinder is fully determined by $c_{11}$. Solving equation (7) gives

\begin{equation*}
c_{11} = -\frac{4 \mu a^{2} B_{0}}{a^{2}\left(\mu + \mu_{0}\right)^{2} - \left(\mu - \mu_{0}\right) b^{2}} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

Thus

$$
\phi_{1} = c_{11} r \cos \theta
$$

The magnetic field is

\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{H}_{1} & = -\nabla \phi_{1} = -\frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial r} \boldsymbol{e}_{r} - \frac{1}{r} \cdot \frac{\partial \phi_{1}}{\partial \theta} \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta} \\
& = -c_{11}\left(\cos \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{r} - \sin \theta \boldsymbol{e}_{\theta}\right) \\
& = -c_{11} \boldsymbol{e}_{z}  \tag{10}\\
& = \frac{4 \mu a^{2}}{a^{2}\left(\mu + \mu_{0}\right)^{2} - \left(\mu - \mu_{0}\right) b^{2}} \boldsymbol{B}_{0}
\end{align*}

When $\mu \gg \mu_{0}$, we have

\begin{equation*}
H_{1} \approx \frac{4}{\mu} \cdot \frac{B_{0}}{1 - \left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^{2}} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}

The larger the $\mu$, the stronger the magnetic shielding effect.

In the absence of an intermediate electrode, if a breakdown occurs, it only reaches the breakdown field strength $E_0$ near the high-voltage electrode, and everywhere else is less than $E_0$. By adding some intermediate electrodes and appropriately distributing the voltage, it is possible to increase the electric field strength at the intermediate electrode to also reach the breakdown field strength $E_0$. This can effectively increase the acceleration voltage. The design should consider making the electric field strength near the outer surface of the intermediate electrode equal to the electric field strength near the high-voltage electrode. This way, as the voltage on the high-voltage electrode increases and the electric field strength at all points increases accordingly, if the gas breaks down, it will do so simultaneously at both locations, thus maximizing the acceleration voltage. A solution similar to approach (a) easily shows that the electric field strength $E(r_1)$ near the outer surface of the intermediate electrode and the electric field strength $E(r_0)$ near the high-voltage electrode satisfy the following relationship:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& E(r_0) = \frac{V_0 - V_1}{r_0^2 \left(\frac{1}{r_0} - \frac{1}{r_1}\right)} \\
& E(r_1) = \frac{V_1 - 0}{r_1^2 \left(\frac{1}{r_0} - \frac{1}{R}\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

Setting $E(r_0) = E(r_1)$, we can solve to find:

$$
\frac{V_1}{V_0} = \frac{1}{1 + \frac{r_0}{r_1} \left(1 - \frac{r_0}{r_1}\right) / \left(1 - \frac{r_1}{R}\right)}
$$

